        "tags": ["core-verbs", "grammar", "b1"],
        "markdown": "# ⚖️ B4 — Ser / Estar / Haber / Tener (B1)\n\n**Goal:** Learn to choose the correct core verb — **ser, estar, haber (hay), tener** — which all mean **to be / to have** but in **different contexts**.\n\n---\n\n## 🧩 Ser — identity / essence\nUse **ser** for **what something is** (permanent):\n\n- Origin / nationality: *Soy de Valencia.*\n- Professions: *Ella es profesora.*\n- Time & dates: *Son las tres.*\n- Material: *La mesa es de madera.*\n\n> 💡 “Ser” = identity / classification (not changing)\n\n---\n\n## 🌡 Estar — state / location\nUse **estar** for **how or where something is** (temporary):\n\n- Emotions: *Estoy cansado.*\n- Location: *El libro está en la mesa.*\n- Temporary conditions: *La sopa está fría.*\n\n> 💡 “Estar” = condition or location (changeable)\n\n---\n\n## 🌍 Haber (hay) — existence\nUse **hay** (from **haber**) to say **there is / there are**:\n\n- *Hay un libro en la mesa.*  \n- *No hay clases hoy.*\n\n> 💡 Use “hay” when introducing something (not describing it)\n\n---\n\n## 🎒 Tener — possession, age, expressions\n- *Tengo un gato.*\n- *Tengo 20 años.*\n- *Tengo hambre / sueño / frío.*\n\n> 💡 “Tener” = to have (own / feel)\n\n---\n\n## ⚡ Common Confusions\n\n| Meaning          | Correct Verb      | Example                           |\n|-----------------|-------------------|----------------------------------|\n| location         | estar             | Madrid **está** en España         |\n| existence        | haber (hay)       | **Hay** un libro en la mesa       |\n| possession       | tener              | **Tengo** un libro                |\n| description      | ser                | El libro **es** interesante       |\n| temporary state  | estar              | Estoy enfermo                     |\n\n---\n\n> 📝 Rule of thumb:  \n> - **ser** = essence  \n> - **estar** = state/location  \n> - **hay** = existence  \n> - **tener** = possession\n",
        "references": []
      }
    ],
